 LockBit Threat Intelligence Notes

A structured breakdown of LockBit ransomware operations from an SOC/DFIR perspective.

---

 Day 1 — Understanding the Threat
 Overview
LockBit is a **Ransomware-as-a-Service (RaaS)** operation that enables affiliates to conduct ransomware attacks using shared tools and infrastructure. It is one of the most active global ransomware families.

Its core strategy is **double extortion**:
- Encrypt victim data
- Exfiltrate sensitive data
- Threaten public leak if ransom is not paid



 Attack Model
- Ransomware-as-a-Service (RaaS)
- Affiliate-driven ecosystem
- Highly automated and scalable
- Global targeting scope

---

 Target Sectors
- Government & public sector
- Healthcare
- Financial services
- Manufacturing
- Energy & critical infrastructure
- Education
- Transportation
- Any internet-exposed organization

---

 Initial Access Techniques
- Phishing / spear-phishing (T1566)
- Valid stolen credentials (T1078)
- Exploited public-facing applications (T1190)
- Exposed RDP services (T1133)
- Drive-by compromise (T1189)

---

Attack Lifecycle (High-Level Flow)
Initial Access → Execution → Privilege Escalation → Lateral Movement → Credential Access → Exfiltration → Encryption → Impact

---

Common Tools Observed
- Cobalt Strike (post-exploitation)
- PsExec (remote execution)
- PowerShell & batch scripts
- Mimikatz / ProcDump (credential dumping)
- 7-Zip (data staging)
- StealBit (data exfiltration)
- Rclone / MEGA (cloud exfiltration)
- AnyDesk / TeamViewer (remote access)

---
Technical Behavior
- AES + ECC encryption
- Multithreaded encryption (fast execution)
- Windows, Linux, and ESXi support
- Shadow copy deletion
- Service termination before encryption
- High-speed ransomware deployment

---

 Evolution Timeline
- **2019:** Initial LockBit release
- **2021:** LockBit 2.0 introduces StealBit + automation
- **2022:** LockBit 3.0 (Black) major upgrade + bug bounty model
- Expansion into multiple platforms and affiliates

---

 Persistence Methods
- Scheduled tasks
- Registry modifications
- Valid account reuse
- Automatic logon configuration

---

 Privilege Escalation
- UAC bypass techniques (UACMe)
- Credential reuse
- Group Policy manipulation
- Exploitation of misconfigurations

---

 Defense Evasion
- Disabling EDR/AV tools
- Clearing Windows event logs
- PowerShell execution bypass
- Software packing / obfuscation
- Self-deletion after execution

---

 Credential Access
- LSASS memory dumping (Mimikatz)
- Browser credential extraction
- Brute force attacks (RDP/VPN)
- Password recovery utilities

---

 Discovery
- Network scanning tools (IP/Port scanners)
- System and domain enumeration
- Share and drive discovery
- Language-based execution filtering

---

 Lateral Movement
- RDP abuse
- SMB / Admin shares
- PsExec execution
- Cobalt Strike movement
- Remote access tools (AnyDesk, TeamViewer)

---

 Exfiltration
- StealBit tool
- Rclone / MEGA cloud storage
- File sharing platforms
- 7-Zip compression before transfer

---

 Impact
- AES + ECC encryption of files
- Shadow copy deletion
- Service termination
- System defacement
- Data destruction

---

 SOC Detection Focus (Important)
Security teams should monitor:
- Suspicious PowerShell execution
- LSASS access attempts
- Rapid file renaming/encryption
- New scheduled tasks creation
- Unusual RDP/SMB activity
- Large outbound data transfers
- Disabled security tools (EDR/AV)

---

 Day 2 — MITRE ATT&CK Mapping & Defensive Analysis

 MITRE ATT&CK Summary
LockBit operations map across multiple ATT&CK tactics:

- Initial Access
- Execution
- Persistence
- Privilege Escalation
- Defense Evasion
- Credential Access
- Discovery
- Lateral Movement
- Collection
- Exfiltration
- Impact

---

 Key Defensive Insight
LockBit attacks are successful due to:
- Rapid execution (low dwell time)
- Use of legitimate tools (Living-off-the-Land)
- Credential abuse instead of malware-heavy tactics
- Strong lateral movement capability
- Double extortion pressure model

---

 Defensive Strategy Mapping
### Prevention
- MFA enforcement
- Patch management (critical CVEs)
- Disable exposed RDP
- Email filtering

 Detection
- PowerShell monitoring
- EDR behavioral alerts
- Credential dumping detection
- Lateral movement detection

Response
- Network segmentation isolation
- Kill compromised sessions
- Block C2 domains
- Restore from clean backups

---

 Final Analyst Takeaway
LockBit is not just malware — it is a **business model-driven cybercrime ecosystem** that combines automation, affiliates, and extortion tactics to maximize financial impact.

